<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec31-scaling" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Scaling Up, Scaling Down</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
        When we think of proportional reasoning, one of the areas of mathematics where we can truly "see" it is 
        geometry.  The ancient Greeks used a very special proportion in their artwork as well as architecture, 
        <em>The Golden Ratio</em>.  This ratio seemed to be found in nature and was deemed pleasing to the eye.  
        In fact, the Fibonacci sequence, <m>\left\{1,1,2,3,5,8,13, \ldots \right\}</m>, has the interesting 
        characteristic that the successive ratios of adjacent terms, <m>\frac{F_n}{F_{n-1}}</m>, approach 
        <em>The Golden Ratio</em> as <m>n \rightarrow \infty</m>.  You may recall that the <em>Golden Ratio</em> 
        occurs when the ratio of the larger of two values to the smaller, <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, is equal to the 
        ratio of the <em>sum</em> of the two values to the larger of the two values.  In other words, when 
        <m>a \gt b \gt 0</m>, we have <m>\frac{a+b}{a}=\frac{a}{b}=\varphi =\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}</m> where 
        <m>\varphi</m> is typically used to represent this ratio. Just like the Fibonacci sequence that is seen 
        throughout nature, <em>The Golden Ratio</em> also seems to be present all around us.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since ratios seem to describe many patterns we see around us, we should consider how the concept of ratio 
      develops in students and try to identify an appropriate place in the curriculum to begin engaging our 
      students with ideas related to ratio and proportion.  When we examine the 
      <em>Common Core State Standards</em>, the first place we see ratio creeping into the curriculum is in 
      Grade 6 (see <xref ref="fig-ccss-grade6-overview"/>).
    </p>
    <p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-ccss-grade6-overview">
        <caption>Overview of the Common Core State Standards for Grade 6</caption>
        <image source="images/ccss-grade6-overview.png" width="90%">
          <shortdescription>Overview of the Common Core State Standards for Grade 6</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </p>

  </introduction>



</section>